# docs/DECISIONS.md

An append-only architectural decision log (ADR-001 through ADR-054, growing) for the CTX project — a context-tree/summarization tooling system with an agent sandboxing subsystem. Each ADR records a decision, rejected alternatives, and rationale; nothing is ever rewritten in place — superseded decisions get a new ADR that references the old one (`[[ADR-NNN]]` cross-link style), and later ADRs sometimes amend or partially retract earlier claims (e.g. ADR-032 corrects an overclaim in ADR-031; ADR-024 is amended by ADR-025).

**Function in the system:** this is the *only* place rationale and rejected alternatives live — `intent.md` files and rollups point here rather than restating it. An editor should treat any curious "why is it built this way" question about CTX as answered here, not in code comments.

**Structural facts an editor needs:**
- Numbering is strictly increasing and sequential; never renumber or delete an entry, even if fully superseded — append a new ADR instead (explicit rule, stated in the file header).
- Heavy internal cross-referencing via `[[ADR-NNN]]` — treat these as load-bearing citations, not decoration; following them is often necessary to understand why a later decision was made.
- Several ADRs document post-hoc incident investigations (e.g. ADR-024/025 tracing a flaky CI false-failure to a filesystem race; ADR-049 tracing 100% CPU burn in a sandboxed process to DNS resolver retry-storms) — these contain specific root-cause narratives, not just decisions, and are useful precedent for future debugging in this codebase.
- The project underwent a major architectural pivot recorded in ADR-035/036/037/040: from a cage-enforced, source-masking, broker-mediated access model to a hook-injected, native-tools, safety-boundary-only sandbox model. Anything describing `ctx-access`, task lifecycle, `served_nodes`, or write-needs-read is describing the **retired** pre-pivot design (superseded by `ctx-context`, hook injection, and CACT hash-based freshness in ADR-038/044/045).
- Most recent entries (ADR-050 through 054) cover: post-run summarize refresh becoming an interactive prompt, retirement of `SPEC.md`/redistribution of its content, orphaned-artifact pruning in `ctx-scan`, and a new `ctx-brief` crate for turning STATUS.md backlog items into executor briefs via two staged `claude -p` calls.

No code lives here and none should be added when editing — this is prose history only, consumed by both humans and LLM agents deciding "why does X work this way" before touching related source.